text.tspan: A constructive approach for graph concepts with long range dependencies
University of Freiburg, Georges-Koehler-Allee 106, D-79110 Freiburg, Germany

flowRoot.flowPara: Reference: Fabrizio Costa. Learning an efficient constructive sampler for graphs. Artif. Intell., 2016
We aim to generate graph instances given examples.

A previous Method repeatedly alters random subgraphs of one of the training graphs and 'accepts' improvements (MCMC/Metropolis-Hastings). This algorithm uses a graph grammar to increase the quality of proposed instances.
We improve the grammar to respect long range dependencies and to operate on arbitrary subgraphs.
We evaluate the new method on RNA structure graphs.
These offer a rich structure and domain specific tools to score the generated instances.

Design goals: instances are vectorized (and normalized) via decomposition kernel, blue (training) and red (new) instances are sharing a probability distribution (indicated by a hyperplane) while being different (non overlapping)

We optimize for two goals: the probability density over the constructed Instances should resemble the distribution of the training set (a loss function over the two distributions) and the created instances should differ from the training instances (measure similarity via graph kernel
). We use as a regulation variable. The task is to find the parameters theta that minimize the loss and the parameters.

The Idea is to Implement a Metropolis-Hastings algorithm for graphs. A discriminator can easily be trained on the training graphs. For the Metropolis algorithm small changes are repeatedly applied to one of the training graphs and the change is probabilistically accepted.
Applying random changes to a graph would yield many low scoring proposals. To mitigate this a graph grammar is used. The grammar applies productions as shown below.
Reference (graph grammar): Grzegorz Rozenberg and Hartmut Ehrig. Handbook of graph grammars and
computing by graph transformation, volume 1. World Scientific, 1999. Also the Metropolis paper obviously.

There are two weaknesses in this scheme: the core is defined in a neighborhood radius around the root (v) and thus inflexible. Another drawback lies in the interface; its thickness (radius around the core) parameter is either small, depicting few constraints and if increased it becomes hard to find congruent instances.
A production is applied:
1. a root node is chosen (v)
2. pick a radius and thickness to determine the core (blue) and the interface (yellow).together these are a CIP (core interface pair)
3. look up if there is a CIP in the database that shares the same interface (isomorphism of light green nodes). Check is quick and easy since interfaces graphs are saved by hash value.
4. apply substitution which will result in the replacement of the cores (dark green).

flowPara.flowSpan: Further illustration of problems on a RNA structure graph. We want to work with a whole stem (dark green). Also stems might depend on each other (green and blue).

flowRoot.flowPara: Our solution is an extension of the grammar. First a coarsened version of the graph (base graph G)

is required. It is obtained by repeatedly contracting any two nodes in the graph (here we contract stems and hairpin loops). A CIP, consisting of core C(G') and interface I(G'), is extracted as before but on the coarsened graph G'. To obtain the new core C(G,G') one looks up the induced graph of the nodes in C(G'). The interface I(G,G') is the Cartesian graph product of a) the interface induced by the neighborhood in radius B of C(G,G') and b) I(G'). With this productions can be applied as before.

Data Selection: RNA polymers cover essential biological roles ranging from coding, decoding,regulation and expression of genes. The RFam database groups known RNA sequences in functionally and evolutionary related families. To empirically investigate the performance of the proposed constructive approach we selected a family (RF01725) which exhibit a rich structure (e.g. that do not consist only of a single hairpin).
Coarsening procedure: The secondary structure of a sequence can not be reliably computed

using the sequence alone. given a candidate sequence we 1) identify k nearest neighbors among the available training instances, then 2) we align the k+1 sequences using the MUSCLE program and compute the consensus structure using the RNAalifold program. This procedure identifies the most representative structure in the ensemble of possible sub optimal solutions. Last 3) we apply the coarsening on the structural elements (see Methods).

Infernal Evaluation: The RFam database contains covariance models for the evaluation of instances in each family. It also contains a human defined bit score threshold. Instances scoring above this threshold can reliably be considered to belong to the family. We used these models
to analyze our generative approach. We also used MUSCLE and RNAalifold to train a new model to compete against (see below).
In the box "Defining the Task" we described the optimization goals for graph construction. By estimating the KullbackLeibler divergence and a graph kernel we can depict both factors (see above).

Conclusion: We presented an approach to construct graphs that factors in long range dependencies. First test results look promising. In future work we will investigate how to learn task specific coarsening schemes in a supervised fashion directly from data to remove the dependence on a coarsening procedure.
